        And empty it was. To give you an idea, anytime our small community was setting up a campsite somewhere, we were instantaneously becoming the biggest and most populated town of the area. All the villages we were passing by had from 10 to 2000 souls, and usually one or two pubs were the only business. To them, the bike ride was quite a special event, making more sales than on New Years Eve.

        Although pretty basic comfort conditions, this volunteering was a lot of fun: You meet a bunch of nice people, all of them being there for having a good time. Also, you live at no expenses and you are given some free stuff away, such as shirts and hats. Moreover it was an amazing opportunity to meet local Australians, as most of the participants were from Victoria despite the huge amount of backpackers in Melbourne.

        I left to Tasmania almost as soon as I came back from the bike ride in order to experience another amazing way to meet locals and live at no expenses while traveling, namely Woofing. The concept is quite simple: you work for someone in exchange of a bed and food. Most of the time, you will be hosted by folks living in an environmentally friendly house remotely from any town in the surrounding, owning a descent piece of land. The odd jobs you are given often relate with entertaining this big piece of land, such as gardening, or digging holes and pouring concrete in order to build an extension to their beloved home.

