        Before I came to Tasmania, I thought hiking there was reserved to an elite of bush walkers like Bear Grylls, only them being able to find their way in the bush and fighting deadly snakes and spiders. Well, I was wrong. Walking in the bush out of the track can be quite dangerous as it is easy to get lost, but it is perfectly safe if you follow the track. There are indeed some spiders and snakes, although they are very shy and will runaway from you rather than jump on your face. When you come down to Australia, you should not be afraid of what can kill you, otherwise you would not go very far out. What you should rather consider is what actually go for you. It turns out that Tasmanian's snakes and spiders are pretty much pacific, most of the nasty things live in Northern Australia, Queensland. Some snakes are aggressive, crocodiles are a real concern and sharks too, along with jellyfishes. But again, except from sharks that strikes randomly (and even then, statistically they strike rarely) you won't have any problem if you listen to your common sense. Crocodiles and jellyfishes are tracked, most of the deadly attack involve too curious tourists.

        What you should be afraid of though is the sunshine, really strong in Australia due to the hole in the ozone layer. It is the country with the most skin cancer per inhabitants, it is therefore witted to always carry some sunscreen and a hat when you go hiking.

        These holidays were really nice, but discussing with locals and sightseeing Tasmania I realized that a car is actually necessary to discover Australia in its all beauty. Even Tasmania is seven times bigger than Corsica.

        Within the next days, I will stay around Melbourne and do some more woofing close to the city. I will give another shot at finding a job on the beginning of January. Also, if I have enough spare time for that, I will upload these letters on my website decorated with some pictures and my one second video project.

        See you soon !<br/>
        Jacques
